    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that's one way to look at it, but isn't that a bit of a circular argument? if i have to raise my prices to pay those higher wages, my customers—who are also in that same small town—will have less money to spend because their own costs are going up. it seems like it could just trigger a downward spiral for small shops. can you explain why some economists say this 'bottom up' theory doesn't always work in practice?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Economists who doubt the \"bottom-up\" theory often focus on the immediate supply-and-demand shock to small businesses. They argue that when labor costs rise suddenly, businesses with thin margins, like many small town cafes, cannot simply absorb the cost or pass it on without losing customers. This can lead to job cuts or reduced service, which is a direct negative impact on the local economy.",
      "source": "target",
